  "prompt": "How much human excreta create by a single person?",
  "response": "The amount of human excreta produced by a single person can vary widely due to factors such as diet, hydration, and individual metabolism. On average, an adult typically produces about 100 to 250 grams (approximately 0.2 to 0.55 pounds) of feces per day. \n\nIn terms of urine, an average person urinates about 800 to 2,000 milliliters (roughly 0.8 to 2 liters) daily, depending on fluid intake and other factors. \n\nThus, if we consider both urine and feces, a single person may produce about 1 to 2.5 liters of urine and 100 to 250 grams of feces each day, leading to a total of approximately 1 to 2.5 liters of human excreta daily, depending on their specific circumstances.",
